Title: Unemployment and Business Cycles 
Author-Name: Lawrence J. Christiano  
Author-Name: Martin S. Eichenbaum  
Author-Name: Mathias Trabandt  
Abstract:
  We develop and estimate a general equilibrium search and matching model
 that accounts for key business cycle properties of macroeconomic
 aggregates, including labor market variables. In sharp contrast to leading
 New Keynesian models, we do not impose wage inertia. Instead we derive
 wage inertia from our specification of how firms and workers negotiate
 wages. Our model outperforms a variant of the standard New Keynesian Calvo
 sticky wage model. According to our estimated model, there is a critical
 interaction between the degree of price stickiness, monetary policy, and
 the duration of an increase in unemployment benefits. 
